                <exercise workspace="4in">
                    <title>Definition: Riemann Sums</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Given <m>f(x)</m> on the interval <m>[a,b]</m>,
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <ol>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        The <term><m>n^{th}</m> right Riemann sum</term> is 
                                        <me>
                                            R_n = \Delta x f(a+\Delta x) + \Delta x f(a+ 2 \Delta x) + \cdots + \Delta x f(a+ n\Delta x) = \Delta x \sum_{k=1}^n f( a+ k\Delta x)
                                        </me>
                                        
                                    </p>
                                </li>

                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        The <term><m>n^{th}</m> left Riemann sum</term> is 
                                        <me>
                                            L_n = \Delta x f(a+ 0\Delta x) + \Delta x f(a+  \Delta x) + \cdots + \Delta x f(a+ (n-1)\Delta x) = \Delta x \sum_{k=0}^{n-1} f( a+ k\Delta x)
                                        </me>
                                        
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>
            <page>
                <exercise workspace="3in">
                    <title>Example: Riemann Sums</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>f(x) = x^2</m> on <m>[0,2]</m>, and choose <m>n=4</m>.
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            Then <m>\Delta x = \frac{2-0}{4} = 0.5</m>, and 
                            <me>
                                R_4 = 0.5 \sum_{n=1}^4 f(0 + n \cdot 0.5) = 0.5(1/4 + 1 + 9/4 + 4) = 15/4
                            </me>,
                            <me>
                                L_4 = 0.5 \sum_{n=0}^3 f(0 + n \cdot 0.5) = 0.5(0+ 1/4 + 1 + 9/4 ) = 7/4
                            </me>.
                            
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>

                <exercise workspace="4in">
                    <title>Positive vs. Negative Function Values</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            See course notes for a visual example. In general, it is important to remember that 
                            Riemann sums approximate the <term>net signed area</term> between a curve and the input axis,
                            where area above the input axis is counted as positive, and area below the input axis is counted
                            as negative.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                    
                </exercise>
